&lt;p&gt;&lt;em&gt;As I Open My Eyes&lt;/em&gt;&amp;nbsp;is set in 2010, shortly before Tunisia&amp;rsquo;s Jasmine Revolution ushered in the upheavals of the Arab Spring. The song, with lyrics by Ghassen Amami and music by the eminent Iraqi oud player Khyam Allami, protests the repressive government of Zine el-Abidine Ben Ali, Tunisia&amp;rsquo;s president for 23 years until he fled the country in 2011. It sets the tone of the film in which word of Farah&amp;rsquo;s dissenting voice reaches the authorities and her safety is endangered.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;This masterclass with&amp;nbsp;Leyla Bouzid&amp;nbsp;will be introduced by Shanny Peer, Director of the Columbia Maison Fran&amp;ccedil;aise, and moderated by Professor Madeleine Dobie.&amp;nbsp;Madeleine Dobie&amp;nbsp;is the Chair and Director of Graduate Studies of the Department of French. Her teaching and research areas include francophone/postcolonial literatures and cinemas of France, the Maghreb, the Middle East and the Caribbean as well as the cultural dimensions of migration and diaspora.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;The masterclass will be held in person and open to those with a Columbia ID. To register for this in person event, please click&amp;nbsp;&lt;a href="https://www.eventbrite.com/e/masterclass-with-leyla-bouzid-tickets-264443847667"&gt;here&lt;/a&gt;. You can also follow the discussion live on&amp;nbsp;&lt;a href="https://www.facebook.com/columbia.maisonfrancaise"&gt;Facebook&lt;/a&gt;.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
